      "writtenOn": "2026-05-04T19:09:47Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e Exactly, so a TMP421 device in your EM config isn\u0027t appropriate here unless you actually have a TMP421.\n\n\u003e That\u0027s fine, then go create a new device type for this sensor and how it behaves.\n\nNo, this is not what we should be doing.\n\nWhat you are asking for requires Alexander to write a kernel driver with the new type.  But he doesn\u0027t have information to even formulate a successful commit message to the kernel let alone a whole new driver.\n\nThe types here are effectively \"compatible\" names; they are not literal device names.  There are other examples already in the EM tree where the \"real\" device isn\u0027t the literal stamped name of the device in a chip either.  But, if it acts like a TMP421, talks like a TMP421, we label it as a TMP421.  This is honestly the same behavior in the kernel and QEMU as well.\n\nTMP421 is a 20+ year old i2c design.  The CX-6 has been GA for over 6 years old.  These things aren\u0027t changing.  Asking the kernel to add a new compatible string just to be \"more explicit\" here isn\u0027t worth the effort it would take to make it happen.",
      "parentUuid": "3f3bcbdc_c69ca4cc",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 20,
        "startChar": 25,
        "endLine": 20,
        "endChar": 32
      },
